0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","article",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__articlePage","children":[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BlogPosting\",\"headline\":\"Fire Pits vs. Fire Tables: Which is Better for Your Custom Deck?\",\"image\":[\"https://www.ldndecks.com/images/img53.jpeg\"],\"datePublished\":\"2026-04-22T04:00:00.000Z\",\"dateModified\":\"2026-04-22T04:00:00.000Z\",\"author\":[{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"Nick - Loudoun Decks\",\"url\":\"https://www.ldndecks.com\"}],\"publisher\":{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"Loudoun Decks\",\"url\":\"https://www.ldndecks.com\",\"logo\":{\"@type\":\"ImageObject\",\"url\":\"https://www.ldndecks.com/ldndecks-logo.webp\"}},\"description\":\"Comparing built-in stone fire pits to portable fire tables for composite decks. Which one offers the best ambiance and safety for your backyard?\",\"mainEntityOfPage\":{\"@type\":\"WebPage\",\"@id\":\"https://www.ldndecks.com/blog/fire-pits-vs-fire-tables-deck\"},\"isAccessibleForFree\":true,\"inLanguage\":\"en-US\",\"speakable\":{\"@type\":\"SpeakableSpecification\",\"cssSelector\":[\".leadParagraph\",\"h1\",\"h2\"]}}"}}],["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__heroSection","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__imgWrapper","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"src":"/images/img53.jpeg","alt":"Fire Pits vs. Fire Tables: Which is Better for Your Custom Deck?","fill":true,"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__heroImg","priority":true,"sizes":"100vw"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__imgOverlay","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__containerLarge","children":[["$","$L3",null,{"href":"/blog","className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__backLink","children":"← Back to News"}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__title","children":"Fire Pits vs. Fire Tables: Which is Better for Your Custom Deck?"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__meta","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__author","children":["By ","Nick - Loudoun Decks"]}],["$","span",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__divider","children":"•"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"April 22, 2026"}]]}]]}]}]]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__contentSection","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__containerNarrow","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__contentBody","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__leadParagraph","children":"Comparing built-in stone fire pits to portable fire tables for composite decks. Which one offers the best ambiance and safety for your backyard?"}],[["$","p","0",{"children":"Nothing transforms a cool Virginia evening like the flicker of a flame. As we design more luxury outdoor spaces in Loudoun County, the question often arises: should we install a permanent stone fire pit or a modern, portable fire table? The choice impacts your deck’s engineering, your budget, and how you use the space throughout the year."}],["$","h2","1",{"style":{"marginTop":"40px","marginBottom":"20px","color":"#111"},"children":"The Permanent Elegance of a Stone Fire Pit"}],["$","p","2",{"children":"A built-in fire pit is a structural statement. Typically constructed with a steel masonry ring and wrapped in natural stone or matching pavers, these features serve as a permanent anchor for your outdoor living room. "}],["$","h3","3",{"style":{"marginTop":"30px","marginBottom":"15px","color":"#222"},"children":"Structural Considerations"}],["$","p","4",{"children":"If you want a stone fire pit on an elevated composite deck, proper engineering is non-negotiable. A stone-and-masonry pit can weigh over 800 pounds. At Loudoun Decks, we must reinforce the structural joists and beams directly beneath the pit with triple-ply framing and additional support posts to prevent the structure from sinking or bowing under the static load."}],"$L4","$L5","$L6","$L7","$L8"],"$L9"]}]}]}],"$La"]}],["$Lb"],"$Lc"]}],"isPartial":false,"staleTime":300,"varyParams":null,"buildId":"Jebrcr4Vyd2YosxlccnHN"}
4:["$","h2","5",{"style":{"marginTop":"40px","marginBottom":"20px","color":"#111"},"children":"The Versatility of Modern Fire Tables"}]
5:["$","p","6",{"children":"For many homeowners, a gas-powered fire table offers a more flexible and modern aesthetic. These items double as functional furniture, providing a surface for drinks and appetizers when the flame is not in use."}]
6:["$","h3","7",{"style":{"marginTop":"30px","marginBottom":"15px","color":"#222"},"children":"Why We Recommend Tables for Composite"}]
7:["$","p","8",{"children":"1. **Heat Management:** Fire tables are typically designed to direct heat upward, protecting the composite boards beneath them. Standard wood-burning pits on a deck require massive thermal shielding or a non-combustible stone \"hearth\" area to be safe.\n2. **Propane vs. Natural Gas:** Most fire tables are plumbed for a 20lb propane tank hidden inside the base, or we can hard-wire a natural gas line directly through the deck boards for infinite fuel.\n3. **Flexibility:** If you decide to rearrange your deck furniture in three years, a fire table can be moved. A stone pit is there forever."}]
8:["$","p","9",{"children":"Ultimately, if you want a rugged, traditional campfire feel, the stone pit is king. If you want a sleek, multi-functional piece of furniture that is safe for sensitive composite materials, the fire table is the winner for 2026."}]
9:["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__conclusionBox","children":[["$","h3",null,{"children":"Ready to upgrade your outdoor living space?"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"Contact Loudoun Decks today for a free estimate and planning consultation."}],["$","$L3",null,{"href":"/contact","className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__ctaBtn","children":"Get Started"}]]}]
